        "name": "Olivier Rioul",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Persistent fault analysis (PFA) consists in guessing block\ncipher secret keys by biasing their substitution box. This paper improves\nthe original attack of Zhang et al. on AES-128 presented at CHES\n2018. By a thorough analysis, the exact probability distribution of the\nciphertext (under a uniformly distributed plaintext) is derived, and the\nmaximum likelihood key recovery estimator is computed exactly. Its\nexpression is turned into an attack algorithm, which is shown to be\ntwice more efficient in terms of number of required encryptions than\nthe original attack of Zhang et al. This algorithm is also optimized\nfrom a computational complexity standpoint. In addition, our optimal\nattack is naturally amenable to key enumeration, which expedites full 16-\nbytes key extraction. Various tradeoffs between data and computational\ncomplexities are investigated.",
    "keywords": [
      "PFA",
      "fault attack",
      "AES"
    ],
    "category": "Secret-key cryptography",
